Here are a few ways to tell the TypeScript type system that a value has a specific, known type in practice:

- Use the as keyword to explicitly specify the type of a variable or expression, e.g. var x = 1 as number;
- Use the type parameter of a generic type to specify a known type, e.g. var x = new List<number>();
- Use the type guard function syntax to specify a known type, e.g. var x = isNumber(1);
- Use the as keyword on a type cast expression to specify the type of the value being cast, e.g. var y = 1 as number;
- Use the type guard function syntax on a type cast expression to specify the type of the value being cast, e.g. var y = isNumber(1);

These are just a few of the many ways to specify the type of a value in TypeScript, but they should be sufficient to express that a value has a specific, known type in practice. Hope this helps!

